014/**
015 * A palette of predefined colors as packed IPT_HQ floats, the kind {@link ColorTools} works with, plus a way to
016 * describe colors by combinations and adjustments. The description code is probably what you would use this class for;
017 * it revolves around {@link #parseDescription(String)}, which takes a color description String and returns a packed
018 * float color. The color descriptions look like "darker rich mint sage", where the order of the words doesn't matter.
019 * They can optionally include lightness changes (light/dark), and saturation changes (rich/dull), and must include one
020 * or more color names that will be mixed together (repeats are allowed to use a color more heavily). The changes can be
021 * suffixed with "er", "est", or "most", such as "duller", "lightest", or "richmost", to progressively increase their
022 * effect on lightness or saturation.
023 * <br>
024 * The rest of this is about the same as in {@link Palette}.
025 * <br>
026 * You can access colors by their constant name, such as {@code CACTUS}, by the {@link #NAMED} map using
027 * {@code NAMED.get("cactus", 0f)}, or by index in the FloatArray called {@link #LIST}. Note that to access a float
028 * color from NAMED, you need to give a default value if the name is not found; {@code 0f} is a good default because it
029 * will not occur in a valid IPT_HQ color. You can access the names in a specific order with {@link #NAMES} (which is
030 * alphabetical), {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE} (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue
031 * (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS} (which is sorted by the intensity of
032 * the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in {@link #NAMED}.
033 * <br>
034 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 10/13/2020.
035 */
036public class SimplePalette {

653    /**
654     * All names for colors in this palette, sorted by lightness from black to white. You can fetch the
655     * corresponding packed float color by looking up a name in {@link #NAMED}.
656     */
657    public static final Array<String> NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS = new Array<>(NAMES);
658    static {
659        NAMES_BY_HUE.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
660            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
661                final float c1 = NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT), c2 = NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT);
662                final float s1 = ColorTools.saturation(c1), s2 = ColorTools.saturation(c2);
663                if(alphaInt(c1) < 128) return -10000;
664                else if(alphaInt(c2) < 128) return 10000;
665                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 > 0.05f)
666                    return -1000;
667                else if(s1 > 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
668                    return 1000;
669                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
670                    return (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.intensity(c1) - ColorTools.intensity(c2));
671                else
672                    return 2 * (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.hue(c1) - ColorTools.hue(c2))
673                            + (int)Math.signum(ColorTools.intensity(c1) - ColorTools.intensity(c2));
674            }
675        });
676        for(String name : NAMES_BY_HUE) {
677            COLORS_BY_HUE.add(NAMED.get(name, TRANSPARENT));
678        }
679        NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
680            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
681                return Float.compare(intensity(NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT)), intensity(NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT)));
682            }
683        });
684    }

686    private static final FloatArray mixing = new FloatArray(4);
687
688    /**
689     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed float color.
690     * Color descriptions consist of one or more lower-case words, separated by non-alphabetical characters (typically
691     * spaces and/or hyphens). Any word that is the name of a color in this SimplePalette will be looked up in
692     * {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name words, the colors will be mixed using
693     * {@link FloatColors#mix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one color name word, then the corresponding color
694     * will be used. The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise,
695     * "rich" and "dull" change the saturation (the difference of the chromatic channels from grayscale). All of these
696     * adjectives can have "-er" or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically,
697     * the chars appended to an adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and
698     * "richcat" is the same as "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are
699     * appended to an adjective (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. If a color
700     * name or adjective is invalid, it is considered the same as adding the color {@link #TRANSPARENT}.
701     * <br>
702     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
703     * and "lightest richer apricot-olive".
704     * @param description a color description, as a lower-case String matching the above format
705     * @return a packed float color as described
706     */
707    public static float parseDescription(final String description) {
708        float intensity = 0f, saturation = 0f;
709        final String[] terms = description.split("[^a-zA-Z]+");
710        mixing.clear();
711        for(String term : terms) {
712            if (term == null || term.isEmpty()) continue;
713            final int len = term.length();
714            switch (term.charAt(0)) {
715                case 'l':
716                    if (len > 2 && term.charAt(2) == 'g') {
717                        switch (len) {
718                            case 9:
719                                intensity += 0.125f;
720                            case 8:
721                                intensity += 0.125f;
722                            case 7:
723                                intensity += 0.125f;
724                            case 5:
725                                intensity += 0.125f;
726                                break;
727                            default:
728                                mixing.add(TRANSPARENT);
729                                break;
730                        }
731                    } else {
732                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
733                    }
734                    break;
735                case 'r':
736                    if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'i') {
737                        switch (len) {
738                            case 8:
739                                saturation += 0.2f;
740                            case 7:
741                                saturation += 0.2f;
742                            case 6:
743                                saturation += 0.2f;
744                            case 4:
745                                saturation += 0.2f;
746                                break;
747                            default:
748                                mixing.add(TRANSPARENT);
749                                break;
750                        }
751                    } else {
752                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
753                    }
754                    break;
755                case 'd':
756                    if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'a') {
757                        switch (len) {
758                            case 8:
759                                intensity -= 0.125f;
760                            case 7:
761                                intensity -= 0.125f;
762                            case 6:
763                                intensity -= 0.125f;
764                            case 4:
765                                intensity -= 0.125f;
766                                break;
767                            default:
768                                mixing.add(TRANSPARENT);
769                                break;
770                        }
771                    } else if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'u') {
772                        switch (len) {
773                            case 8:
774                                saturation -= 0.2f;
775                            case 7:
776                                saturation -= 0.2f;
777                            case 6:
778                                saturation -= 0.2f;
779                            case 4:
780                                saturation -= 0.2f;
781                                break;
782                            default:
783                                mixing.add(TRANSPARENT);
784                                break;
785                        }
786                    } else {
787                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
788                    }
789                    break;
790                default:
791                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, TRANSPARENT));
792                    break;
793            }
794        }
795        float result = FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixing.size);
796
797        if(intensity > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, intensity);
798        else if(intensity < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -intensity);
799
800        if(saturation > 0) result = ColorTools.enrich(result, saturation);
801        else if(saturation < 0) result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(ColorTools.dullen(result, -saturation));
802        else result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(result);
803
804        return result;
805    }
806    private static final Array<String> namesByHue = new Array<>(NAMES_BY_HUE);
807    private static final FloatArray colorsByHue = new FloatArray(COLORS_BY_HUE);
808    static {
809        int trn = namesByHue.indexOf("transparent", false);
810        namesByHue.removeIndex(trn);
811        colorsByHue.removeIndex(trn);
812    }
813    /**
814     * Given a color as a packed IPT_HQ float, this finds the closest description it can to match the given color while
815     * using at most {@code mixCount} colors to mix in. You should only use small numbers for mixCount, like 1 to 3;
816     * this can take quite a while to run otherwise. This returns a String description that can be passed to
817     * {@link #parseDescription(String)}. It is likely that this will use very contrasting colors if mixCount is 2 or
818     * greater and the color to match is desaturated or brownish.
819     * @param ipt_hq a packed IPT_HQ float color to attempt to match
820     * @param mixCount how many color names this will use in the returned description
821     * @return a description that can be fed to {@link #parseDescription(String)} to get a similar color
822     */
823    public static String bestMatch(final float ipt_hq, int mixCount) {
824        mixCount = Math.max(1, mixCount);
825        float bestDistance = Float.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
826        final int paletteSize = namesByHue.size, colorTries = (int)Math.pow(paletteSize, mixCount), totalTries = colorTries * 81;
827        final float targetI = ColorTools.intensity(ipt_hq), targetP = ColorTools.protan(ipt_hq), targetT = ColorTools.tritan(ipt_hq);
828        final String[] lightAdjectives = {"darkmost ", "darkest ", "darker ", "dark ", "", "light ", "lighter ", "lightest ", "lightmost "};
829        final String[] satAdjectives = {"dullmost ", "dullest ", "duller ", "dull ", "", "rich ", "richer ", "richest ", "richmost "};
830        mixing.clear();
831        for (int i = 0; i < mixCount; i++) {
832            mixing.add(colorsByHue.get(0));
833        }
834        int bestCode = 0;
835        for (int c = 0; c < totalTries; c++) {
836            for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; i++, e *= paletteSize) {
837                mixing.set(i, colorsByHue.get((c / e) % paletteSize));
838            }
839            int idxI = ((c / colorTries) % 9 - 4), idxS = (c / (colorTries * 9) - 4);
840            float intensity = idxI * 0.125f, saturation = idxS * 0.2f;
841
842            float result = FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixCount);
843            if(intensity > 0) result = ColorTools.lighten(result, intensity);
844            else if(intensity < 0) result = ColorTools.darken(result, -intensity);
845
846            if(saturation > 0) result = ColorTools.enrich(result, saturation);
847            else if(saturation < 0) result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(ColorTools.dullen(result, -saturation));
848            else result = ColorTools.limitToGamut(result);
849
850            float dI = ColorTools.intensity(result) - targetI, dP = ColorTools.protan(result) - targetP, dT = ColorTools.tritan(result) - targetT;
851            if(bestDistance > (bestDistance = Math.min(dI * dI * 3f + dP * dP + dT * dT, bestDistance)))
852                bestCode = c;
853        }
854
855        StringBuilder description = new StringBuilder(lightAdjectives[(bestCode / colorTries) % 9] + satAdjectives[bestCode / (colorTries * 9)]);
856        for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; e *= paletteSize) {
857            description.append(namesByHue.get((bestCode / e) % paletteSize));
858            if(++i < mixCount)
859                description.append(' ');
860        }
861        return description.toString();
862    }

864    /**
865     * Changes the existing RGBA Color instances in {@link Colors} to use IPT_HQ and so be able to be shown normally by
866     * {@link ColorfulBatch} or a Batch using {@link com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.Shaders#fragmentShaderIPT_HQ}.
867     * Any colors used in libGDX text markup look up their values in Colors, so calling this can help display fonts
868     * where markup is enabled. This only needs to be called once, and if you call {@link #appendToKnownColors()}, then
869     * that should be done after this to avoid mixing RGBA and IPT_HQ colors.
870     * <br>
871     * This is a duplicate of a method with the same name in Palette; you should still only call this method once,
872     * regardless of where it was from.
873     */
874    public static void editKnownColors(){
875        for(Color c : Colors.getColors().values()) {
876            final float f = ColorTools.fromColor(c);
877            c.set(intensity(f), protan(f), tritan(f), c.a);
878        }
879    }

882     * Appends IPT_HQ-compatible Color instances to the map in {@link Colors}, using the names in {@link #NAMES} (which
883     * are "lower cased" instead of "ALL UPPER CASE"). If you intend to still use the existing values in Colors, you
884     * should call {@link #editKnownColors()} first; otherwise you can just always use "lower cased" color names.
885     * <br>
886     * This can be used alongside the method with the same name in Palette, since that uses "Title Cased" names.
887     */
888    public static void appendToKnownColors(){
889        for(ObjectFloatMap.Entry<String> ent : NAMED) {
890            final float f = ent.value;
891            Colors.put(ent.key, new Color(intensity(f), protan(f), tritan(f), alpha(f)));
892        }
